{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17535558","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17535558"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T16:57:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T16:57:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15488"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15488","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15488"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.73,0.24,0.02,0.01]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8179"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89958"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8179","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8179"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15488"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74117"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1127"},{"type":"tags","id":"1265"},{"type":"tags","id":"3189"},{"type":"tags","id":"3343"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"8971"},{"type":"tags","id":"8972"},{"type":"tags","id":"9040"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30642"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89958","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89958"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department after collapsing during a marathon on a hot summer day. The ambient temperature is 35\u00b0C with high humidity. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He had been running for three hours before collapse and had consumed minimal water.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears confused and agitated. His pulse rate is 130/min, blood pressure 100/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 28/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and core temperature 41.2\u00b0C. His skin is hot and dry. He has reduced consciousness with a Glasgow Coma Scale score of 13/15.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate first step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Antipyretic medication","Immediate active cooling","Intravenous fluid resuscitation","Transfer to intensive care unit","Blood cultures and broad-spectrum antibiotics"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of heat stroke, defined by a core temperature above 40\u00b0C accompanied by central nervous system dysfunction. The presentation during intense physical activity in hot, humid conditions (exertional heat stroke) makes the diagnosis clear.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EImmediate active cooling\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important first step in management of heat stroke. Rapid cooling should be initiated as soon as possible, as the duration of hyperthermia correlates with poor outcomes. Methods include ice water immersion, evaporative cooling with fans, or ice packs to major vessels.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntravenous fluid resuscitation\u003C/strong\u003E is important but secondary to cooling. While the patient is likely dehydrated, the immediate threat to life is from hyperthermia rather than hypovolaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETransfer to intensive care unit\u003C/strong\u003E will likely be necessary but should not delay immediate cooling measures. The priority is to lower the core temperature as quickly as possible.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntipyretic medication\u003C/strong\u003E such as paracetamol is not effective in heat stroke as the condition represents a failure of thermoregulation rather than a reset hypothalamic set point as seen in fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlood cultures and broad-spectrum antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate for sepsis, which can present similarly. However, the clear history of extreme physical exertion in hot conditions makes heat stroke the more likely diagnosis, and cooling should not be delayed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key principle in managing heat stroke is that rapid cooling takes precedence over other interventions. The target is to reduce core temperature to below 39\u00b0C within 30 minutes of presentation. After cooling is initiated, attention can be turned to fluid resuscitation and other supportive measures.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Heat stroke is defined by core temperature above 40\u00b0C with central nervous system dysfunction.","Immediate cooling is the priority in heat stroke management, before transport to hospital.","Cessation of physical activity and moving to a cool environment are critical first steps in managing heat-related illness."],"references":["Bouchama A, Dehbi M, Chaves-Carballo E. Cooling and hemodynamic management in heatstroke: practical recommendations. Critical Care. 2007;11(3):R54.\u200c","Sankoff J. Heat illnesses: a hot topic in the setting of global climate change. Aust Fam Physician. 2015 Jan-Feb;44(1-2):22-6. PMID: 25688955. [cited 2025 Mar 11] Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/afp/2015/january-february/heat-illnesses-a-hot-topic-in-the-setting-of-globa"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74117"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15488"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74117","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74117"},"attributes":{